{
  "answer": "**In the *Manusmṛti* (also known as the *Laws of Manu*), Chapter 3, the text enumerates eight forms of marriage (verses Mn_3.20–21).**[^1]\n\nThe passage introduces them as follows:\n\n> [p-36d967] Now learn in summary these eight forms of marriage for women, for the four *varnas*, which are beneficial and harmful in this world and the next. // Mn_3.20 //  \n> [p-b07c61] The `Brāhma`, the `Daiva`, and also the `Ārṣa`; the `Prājāpatya` and the `Āsura`; the `Gāndharva` and the `Rākṣasa`; and the eighth and lowest, the `Paiśāca`. // Mn_3.21 //\n\nThese match the query's descriptions: the *Gāndharva* rite is \"the voluntary union of a maiden and her lover... which springs from desire\" (Mn_3.32);[^2] the *Rākṣasa* is \"the forcible abduction of a maiden... after her kinsmen have been slain, wounded\" (Mn_3.33);[^3] and the *Paiśāca* is when \"a man secretly approaches a girl who is sleeping, intoxicated... the eighth and most wicked\" (Mn_3.34).[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 3, paragraphs p-36d967 and p-b07c61](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/03/translation/#p-36d967).\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 3, paragraph p-beb0f2](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/03/translation/#p-beb0f2).\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 3, paragraph p-2f28cf](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/03/translation/#p-2f28cf).\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 3, paragraph p-ca03b2](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/03/translation/#p-ca03b2).",
